<Tabs id="final_email_tab">

<Vertical id="tab1" title="The Final Email">
<Markdown>
### Write the final email
</Markdown>
<TextArea id="final_email" rows="10" />
</Vertical>

<Vertical id="tab2" title="JJ's Outline">
<Markdown>
1. _Why Annie's Friend Shouldn't Give Up On Setting Bedtime._

   Don't give up on the bedtime yet -- I really think we can turn this around! A consistent bedtime is one of the most reliable things for a six-year-old: better sleep, better behavior, more security. The plan isn't broken; we just need to adjust the approach until we find what works.
</Markdown>
<Markdown>
2. _What psychological technique we are recommending._

    To encourage a child to go to bed at bedtime, it's a great idea
    to use positive reinforcement.

3. _Explanation of what positive reinforcement is and why it works._

    Instead of focusing on what the child is doing wrong, positive
    reinforcement highlights and rewards good behavior, making it
    more likely to happen again in the future.

    Positive reinforcement is effective because it strengthens the
    behavior you want to see. Instead of focusing on what the child
    might do "wrong," this method encourages compliance and cooperation
    by creating positive associations with bedtime. Children are more
    likely to repeat behaviors that earn them rewards and praise, and
    they feel more motivated when they know their actions are recognized
    in a positive way.

4. _List of positive reinforcement techniques she can use to try to get the kid to go to bed at bedtime._

    **Sticker Chart**: Reward each on-time bedtime with a sticker to
    track progress visually.

    **Bedtime Story**: Offer a favorite bedtime story as a reward for
    getting into bed on time.

    **Special Night Light**: Let them choose a fun night light or glowing toy
    for their room.

    **Cozy Blanket**: Reward with a special cozy blanket or plush pillow
    for their efforts.

5. _Final paragraph -- wish her luck!_

   I hope with this advice, your next babysitting gig goes much better.
</Markdown>
</Vertical>

<Vertical id="tab3" title="Lin's Outline">
<Markdown>
1. _Why Annie's Friend Shouldn't Give Up On Setting Bedtime._

   I'd encourage you not to abandon a consistent bedtime. Predictable routines are strongly linked to healthy sleep and behavior in young children, and removing that structure usually makes things harder, not easier. The trouble so far isn't a sign that bedtimes don't work -- it's a sign the strategy needs adjusting.
</Markdown>
<Markdown>
2. _What psychological technique we are recommending._

   Using positive reinforcement is an effective way to encourage a child
   to go to bed at bedtime.

3. _Explanation of what positive reinforcement is and why it works._

   Positive reinforcement involves rewarding the child when they perform
   the desired behavior, which increases the likelihood that they will
   repeat it in the future.

   It helps establish a clear connection between the desired behavior
   (going to bed on time) and the rewarding outcome. This approach
   encourages the child to view bedtime as a positive experience rather
   than something to resist, fostering motivation and cooperation over
   time. By focusing on rewarding good behavior rather than punishing
   noncompliance, the child is more likely to feel empowered and develop
   healthy habits.

4. _List of positive reinforcement techniques she can use to try to get the kid to go to bed at bedtime._

   **Sing a Lullaby**: Offer to sing their favorite lullaby if they go
   to bed without delay.

   **Golden Star Award**: Create a "Golden Star" award for being a
   good bedtime hero.

   **Pajama Party Theme**: Let them pick fun pajamas as part of
   bedtime preparation.

   **Countdown Timer**: Use a timer with a cheerful tune to make bedtime
   feel exciting.

   **Bedtime Snack**: Reward with a small, healthy snack like fruit or
   yogurt before bed.

5.  _Final paragraph -- wish her luck!_

    With luck, this will help!
</Markdown>
</Vertical>

<Vertical id="tab4" title="Annie's Outline">
<Markdown>
1. _Why Annie's Friend Shouldn't Give Up On Setting Bedtime._

   Okay, so I know it feels like nothing's working, but please don't give up on a bedtime. Every kid I've been around does better with a routine they can count on -- it's easier on everybody once it clicks. The bedtime isn't the problem; we just haven't found the thing that works for him yet.
</Markdown>
<Markdown>
2. _What psychological technique we are recommending._

   Positive reinforcement is a powerful strategy to encourage desired
   behaviors in children, such as going to bed at bedtime.

3. _Explanation of what positive reinforcement is and why it works._

   Positive reinforcement involves providing a desirable reward or
   incentive after the desired behavior occurs, increasing the likelihood
   that the behavior will be repeated.

   It is effective because it motivates behavior through encouragement
   rather than conflict. Children are more likely to cooperate when they
   know their efforts will be recognized and appreciated. Additionally,
   it helps build their sense of accomplishment and strengthens their
   ability to follow routines, which is crucial for their development.
   By using positive reinforcement, you create a routine that feels
   rewarding and enjoyable for the child, making it easier for them
   to develop healthy habits over time.


4. _List of positive reinforcement techniques she can use to try to get the kid to go to bed at bedtime._

    **Bedtime Buddy**: Allow them to sleep with their favorite stuffed animal
    or toy.

    **Favorite Song**: Play one favorite soothing song before lights out
    as a reward.

    **Superhero Role**: Call them a "bedtime superhero" for helping achieve
    their goals.

    **Magical Bedtime Passport**: Stamp their bedtime passport for every
    on-time bed night.

    **Calming Scents**: Reward with a choice of calming scents like
    lavender-scented mist for their room

5.  _Final paragraph -- wish her luck!_

    I hope these techniques make your next babysitting experience a lot easier!
</Markdown>
</Vertical>

